3. Native lambda notation
Typing function(x) f(x) to declare an anonymous function is long, so rlang (a pillar of the #tidyverse) came up with ~ f(.x).
Now #rstats has something in between: \(x) f(x)
It's a tad longer but it has benefits too (e.g it can accept several arguments) https://t.co/cSzGIBdGim

#rstats version 4.1 is out!

Here are our 3 favorite new features:
1. combining 2 factors now keeps all levels
2. a native pipe
3. a native lambda notation

All these features have #tidyverse precursors

Continue the thread for explanations, illustrations and a bonus feature! 👇

1. Combining factors
Before #rstats 4.1, c(factor(c("a", "b")), factor(c("b", "c"))) would yield a vector of integers 😖
Since levels are not the same, R dropped them, and the factors would thus become plain integers. 
Now you get a b b c (as in #tidyverse forcats::fct_c()) https://t.co/eqVmq8XXIa

2. Native pipe
There is a new native pipe in #rstats!: |>
It is not as flexible as the famous magrittr %>% used in #tidyverse dplyr (no target "." can be defined, requires parentheses for fn calls) 
But it may suffice in most cases
The | and > are also close on the keyboard https://t.co/gLgRukZ1Ep

- it's faster than %>% (even the new one in C) so if you have a pipeline in a loop you might prefer native for that
